          "body": "Verse 3 is the chapter's most theologically fraught statement: 'I will harden Pharaoh's heart that I may multiply My signs and My wonders.' The announcement precedes any plague, any sign, any confrontation — it is God's pre-declared sovereign purpose. The difficulty is real and must not be minimized. Reformed interpreters, following Jonathan Edwards and Calvin's commentary on Exodus, read the hardening as God's judicial act — giving Pharaoh over to the disposition already latent within him (Romans 1:24, 26, 28 use the same giving-over logic). Classical Arminian interpreters (Arminius himself; Wesley) argue that God's foreknowledge of Pharaoh's free choices informs the announcement, and that the hardening is consequential — God hardens by multiplying signs that an already-resistant heart refuses. Critically, the chapter uses two distinct verbs: qashah (7:3, God's action — to make stiff) and chazaq (7:13, 22 — the heart is/became hardened), and Pharaoh's moral culpability is never removed: he 'refuses' (7:14), and his indifference is presented as moral failure (7:23). Paul's sustained argument in Romans 9:14-18, citing Exodus 9:16 and 33:19, treats the hardening as a specimen of unconditional divine sovereignty. The chapter holds both God's announced causation (7:3) and Pharaoh's genuine moral agency (7:14, 23) in tension that neither the text nor this study will prematurely dissolve."
