          "body": "The chapter closes with two images that together define the texture of hardened unbelief. First, the magicians replicate the plague (7:22) — not to undo it but to imitate it, which is Pharaoh's preferred response to Yahweh's power: find a counter-narrative that makes acknowledgment unnecessary. Second, 'Pharaoh turned and went into his house with no concern even for this' (7:23). The Hebrew phrase translated 'no concern' is literally 'he did not set his heart to it' — the same vocabulary of lev (heart) used throughout the hardening. He refused to let the plague land on his heart. Meanwhile, all the Egyptians dug around the Nile for water (7:24) — the common people suffered what the king would not acknowledge. Swindoll (Moses: A Man of Selfless Dedication) rightly observes that Pharaoh's indifference to his people's suffering is itself a judgment: hardness of heart toward God produces callousness toward the human beings God made in His image. The seven days of 7:25 close the plague-episode as a completed unit, one of ten, each escalating in severity, each met by the same trajectory: judgment → magicians' imitation → hardening → fulfillment formula."
